{"title_page": "Tivoli Audio", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n{{peacock|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Tivoli Audio\n| logo = \n| trading_name = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| native_name = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-2 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{tl|lang}}, instead. -->\n| type = \n| traded_as = \n| industry = \n| genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| founder = Tom DeVesto\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| area_served = \n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|Paul De Pasquale ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])}}\n| products = {{Unbulleted list|[[Tivoli Audio PAL]]|[[Tivoli Audio Model One]]|[[Tivoli Audio Model One Digital]]}}\n| production = \n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = 30+\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n| caption = \n| romanized = \n| former type = \n| foundation = 2000\n| location_city = Boston, MA\n| location_country = \n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices &c. -->\n| homepage = https://www.tivoliaudio.com\n| bodystyle = \n}}\n\n'''Tivoli Audio''' is an American audio manufacturing company which sells audio products. It was founded in 2000 by Tom DeVesto in collaboration with [[Henry Kloss]], who noticed a gap in the consumer audio market for a high-quality, well designed and affordable AM/FM radio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://totallywired.co.nz/tivoli-history.html|title=Totally Wired - The Tivoli Audio history and design|website=totallywired.co.nz|language=en|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref> Tivoli Audio is best known for its Model One Radio.\n\n==History==\nThe Company was founded in Massachusetts in 2000 by legendary audio engineer Henry Kloss and entrepreneur Tom DeVesto, who noticed a gap in the consumer audio market for high-quality, well designed and affordable audio products. Their first product was the Model One, a simple to use mid-century modern designed table top radio with a high-performance tuner, receiving FM radio in congested urban locations, while maintaining the ability to pick out distant or low power stations. Kloss had noted that the mid 60's wave of Japanese radios lacked the ability to receive FM stations in congested locations, and this became a defining goal of his radio designs throughout his career. Kloss passed away in 2002, but Tivoli Audio continued. By 2006, Tivoli Audio had become a global luxury brand, selling in over 30 countries and gaining recognition in the audio and design world. \n  \nAs of 2015, the company is operated under new management consisting of Tivoli Audio veterans Paul DePasquale, Chief Executive Officer & Designer, and Dan Atanasov, Chief Financial Officer.  They have developed new products, ideas and opportunities to further diverse and steer Tivoli Audio as a lifestyle brand. DePasquale developed the initiative to connect the brand with the hospitality industry, focusing on products and practices, which have led to global partnerships with [[The Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company|Ritz Carlton]], [[Marriott Hotels]] and [[Ace Hotels|Ace Hotels]] using Tivoli Audio products to enhance their guest\u2019s stay. In 2016, Tivoli Audio launched the ART wireless collection, injecting the latest in audio technology and music features, such as wi-fi streaming and Spotify Connect, while staying true to luxury designs and quality craftsmanship. The company also has continued to explore unique partnerships to expand the brand\u2019s lifestyle approach with new collaborations, such as the 2018 limited-edition model with global fashion brand Supreme.\n \nAs of 2019, Tivoli Audio opened a flagship showroom and shop on Boston's [[Newbury Street|Newbury Street]].\n\n==Products==\n \nAfter the Model One, Tivoli Audio continued to produce and release products that were true to their mission statement, making simple-to-use high-quality audio products at a fair price. The next decade saw many new releases such as the PAL (Portable Audio Laboratory), Model Three (Alarm Clock Radio) and the All-in-one Music System, to name a few. The [[Digital audio broadcasting|DAB]]+ product range portable PAL+ and PAL+BT received awards and excellent reviews over the years for best portable radio as well as best tested from Lyd & Bilde<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lydogbilde.no/test/hi-fi/tivoli-audio-pal-bt|title=TEST: Tivoli Audio PAL+ BT - Det beste kj\u00f8pet|website=Lyd & Bilde|language=nb-NO|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>. This range of products, recognizable with the + in the product name experienced great succes in Scandinavian DAB+ countries like Denmark and Norway since their introductions following the PAL+ in 2011.In 2016 Tivoli Audio further diversified their product line by releasing the ART Collection, merging high quality audio, wireless streaming and smart home technology in an range of mid-century modern designs.\n\nTivoli has released many collaborations and special collections, fully recognizing the consumer demand for custom made products. Different styles and finishes were released and collaborations forged between Tivoli and brands like [[Coach, Inc.|Coach]], [[Cappellini|Cappallini]], [[Anthropology|Anthropology]], [[NPR]], and [[Supreme (brand)|Supreme]].\n\n==Product release timeline==\n* '''2000:'''  Model One AM/FM Radio\n* '''2001:'''  Model Two AM/FM Radio Stereo with subwoofer and CD player\n* '''2002:'''  PAL (Portable Audio Laboratory)\n* '''2003:'''  Model Three Alarm Clock Radio with subwoofer and extra speaker\n* '''2004:'''  Songbook AM/FM Alarm clock travel radio\n* '''2005:'''  iSongbook Portable Music System with built-in [[iPod]] dock\n* '''2006:'''  Music System All-in-one stereo system\n* '''2007:'''  iYiYi High-Fidelity stereo system for iPod \n* '''2008:'''  Networks Global Audio System with internet capabilities, stereo speaker and CD player  \n* '''2010:'''  Model 10 AM/FM clock radio; The Connector iPod dock\n* '''2011:'''  PAL+ Portable radio with DAB/DAB+/FM\n* '''2012''':  Model One Bluetooth, PAL BT, Model Three Bluetooth, BlueCon Music Receiver with Bluetooth connectivity, redesign of the Music System to include Bluetooth (Music System BT) and DAB+ (Music System+)\n* '''2013:'''  Albergo AM/FM clock radio with Bluetooth as well as the DAB+ variant, the Albergo+\n* '''2014:'''  Music System Three portable Hi-Fi system with AM/FM and BlueTooth connectivity as well as the DAB+ variant (Music System Three+), PAL+BT Portable radio with DAB/DAB+/FM/Bluetooth\n* '''2016:'''  Art Collection Orb/Sphera, Cube, ConX, limited edition PAL BT GLO \n* '''2017:'''  ART Collection Model One Digital, Model One Digital+, Model Sub (Wifi), Model CD (WiFi)\n*'''2018:'''  The PAL+BT received a redesign as well as limited edition models, Tivoli Go line: Andiamo Bluetooth Speaker & Fonico Wireless Stereo Earbuds, Music System Home Hi-Fi system with Amazon Alexa/CD/FM/DAB+,        WiFi and BlueTooth connectivity (DAB+ in selected countries only)\n*'''2019:'''  Revive (desktop lamp and bluetooth speaker with wireless phone charging)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://tivoliaudio.com/|Official US website}}\n\n[[Category:Audio equipment manufacturers of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n{{peacock|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Tivoli Audio\n| logo = \n| trading_name = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| native_name = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-2 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{tl|lang}}, instead. -->\n| type = \n| traded_as = \n| industry = \n| genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| founder = Tom DeVesto\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| area_served = \n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|Paul De Pasquale ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])}}\n| products = {{Unbulleted list|[[Tivoli Audio PAL]]|[[Tivoli Audio Model One]]|[[Tivoli Audio Model One Digital]]}}\n| production = \n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = 30+\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n| caption = \n| romanized = \n| former type = \n| foundation = 2000\n| location_city = Boston, MA\n| location_country = \n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices &c. -->\n| homepage = https://www.tivoliaudio.com\n| bodystyle = \n}}\n\n'''Tivoli Audio''' is an American audio manufacturing company which sells audio products. It was founded in 2000 by Tom DeVesto in collaboration with [[Henry Kloss]], who noticed a gap in the consumer audio market for a high-quality, well designed and affordable AM/FM radio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://totallywired.co.nz/tivoli-history.html|title=Totally Wired - The Tivoli Audio history and design|website=totallywired.co.nz|language=en|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref> Tivoli Audio is best known for its Model One Radio.\n\n==History==\nThe Company was founded in Massachusetts in 2000 by legendary audio engineer Henry Kloss and entrepreneur Tom DeVesto, who noticed a gap in the consumer audio market for high-quality, well designed and affordable audio products. Their first product was the Model One, a simple to use mid-century modern designed table top radio with a high-performance tuner, receiving FM radio in congested urban locations, while maintaining the ability to pick out distant or low power stations. Kloss had noted that the mid 60's wave of Japanese radios lacked the ability to receive FM stations in congested locations, and this became a defining goal of his radio designs throughout his career. Kloss passed away in 2002, but Tivoli Audio continued. By 2006, Tivoli Audio had become a global luxury brand, selling in over 30 countries and gaining recognition in the audio and design world. \n  \nAs of 2015, the company is operated under new management consisting of Tivoli Audio veterans Paul DePasquale, Chief Executive Officer & Designer, and Dan Atanasov, Chief Financial Officer.  They have developed new products, ideas and opportunities to further diverse and steer Tivoli Audio as a lifestyle brand. DePasquale developed the initiative to connect the brand with the hospitality industry, focusing on products and practices, which have led to global partnerships with [[The Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company|Ritz Carlton]], [[Marriott Hotels]] and [[Ace Hotels|Ace Hotels]] using Tivoli Audio products to enhance their guest\u2019s stay. In 2016, Tivoli Audio launched the ART wireless collection, injecting the latest in audio technology and music features, such as wi-fi streaming and Spotify Connect, while staying true to luxury designs and quality craftsmanship. The company also has continued to explore unique partnerships to expand the brand\u2019s lifestyle approach with new collaborations, such as the 2018 limited-edition model with global fashion brand Supreme.\n \nAs of 2019, Tivoli Audio opened a flagship showroom and shop on Boston's [[Newbury Street|Newbury Street]].\n\n==Products==\n \nAfter the Model One, Tivoli Audio continued to produce and release products that were true to their mission statement, making simple-to-use high-quality audio products at a fair price. The next decade saw many new releases such as the PAL (Portable Audio Laboratory), Model Three (Alarm Clock Radio) and the All-in-one Music System, to name a few. The [[Digital audio broadcasting|DAB]]+ product range portable PAL+ and PAL+BT received awards and excellent reviews over the years for best portable radio as well as best tested from Lyd & Bilde<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lydogbilde.no/test/hi-fi/tivoli-audio-pal-bt|title=TEST: Tivoli Audio PAL+ BT - Det beste kj\u00f8pet|website=Lyd & Bilde|language=nb-NO|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>. This range of products, recognizable with the + in the product name experienced great succes in Scandinavian DAB+ countries like Denmark and Norway since their introductions following the PAL+ in 2011.In 2016 Tivoli Audio further diversified their product line by releasing the ART Collection, merging high quality audio, wireless streaming and smart home technology in an range of mid-century modern designs.\n\nTivoli has released many collaborations and special collections, fully recognizing the consumer demand for custom made products. Different styles and finishes were released and collaborations forged between Tivoli and brands like [[Coach, Inc.|Coach]], [[Cappellini|Cappallini]], [[Anthropology|Anthropology]], [[NPR]], and [[Supreme]].\n\n==Product release timeline==\n* '''2000:'''  Model One AM/FM Radio\n* '''2001:'''  Model Two AM/FM Radio Stereo with subwoofer and CD player\n* '''2002:'''  PAL (Portable Audio Laboratory)\n* '''2003:'''  Model Three Alarm Clock Radio with subwoofer and extra speaker\n* '''2004:'''  Songbook AM/FM Alarm clock travel radio\n* '''2005:'''  iSongbook Portable Music System with built-in [[iPod]] dock\n* '''2006:'''  Music System All-in-one stereo system\n* '''2007:'''  iYiYi High-Fidelity stereo system for iPod \n* '''2008:'''  Networks Global Audio System with internet capabilities, stereo speaker and CD player  \n* '''2010:'''  Model 10 AM/FM clock radio; The Connector iPod dock\n* '''2011:'''  PAL+ Portable radio with DAB/DAB+/FM\n* '''2012''':  Model One Bluetooth, PAL BT, Model Three Bluetooth, BlueCon Music Receiver with Bluetooth connectivity, redesign of the Music System to include Bluetooth (Music System BT) and DAB+ (Music System+)\n* '''2013:'''  Albergo AM/FM clock radio with Bluetooth as well as the DAB+ variant, the Albergo+\n* '''2014:'''  Music System Three portable Hi-Fi system with AM/FM and BlueTooth connectivity as well as the DAB+ variant (Music System Three+), PAL+BT Portable radio with DAB/DAB+/FM/Bluetooth\n* '''2016:'''  Art Collection Orb/Sphera, Cube, ConX, limited edition PAL BT GLO \n* '''2017:'''  ART Collection Model One Digital, Model One Digital+, Model Sub (Wifi), Model CD (WiFi)\n*'''2018:'''  The PAL+BT received a redesign as well as limited edition models, Tivoli Go line: Andiamo Bluetooth Speaker & Fonico Wireless Stereo Earbuds, Music System Home Hi-Fi system with Amazon Alexa/CD/FM/DAB+,        WiFi and BlueTooth connectivity (DAB+ in selected countries only)\n*'''2019:'''  Revive (desktop lamp and bluetooth speaker with wireless phone charging)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://tivoliaudio.com/|Official US website}}\n\n[[Category:Audio equipment manufacturers of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSupreme(link changed toSupreme (brand)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tivoli_Audio"}
{"title_page": "2017 Euro Beach Soccer League", "text_new": "{{Infobox international football competition\n| tourney_name = Euro Beach Soccer League\n| year = 2017\n| dates = 23 June \u2013 17 September\n| other_titles =\n| image = 2017 EBSL Superfinal logo.png\n| size = \n| caption = Logo the Superfinal of the 2017 EBSL\n| num_teams = 27\n| confederations = 1\n| country = Serbia\n| country2 = Portugal\n| country3 = Russia\n| country4 = Hungary\n| country5 = Germany\n| country6 = Italy\n| venues = 6\n| cities = 6\n| champion_other = {{beachsoccer|RUS}}\n| count = 5\n| second_other = {{beachsoccer|POR}}\n| third_other = {{beachsoccer|ITA}}\n| fourth_other = {{beachsoccer|ESP}}\n| matches = 89\n| goals = 727\n| attendance =\n| top_scorer = \n| player = \n| goalkeeper = \n| updated =\n| prevseason = [[2016 Euro Beach Soccer League|2016]]\n| nextseason = [[2018 Euro Beach Soccer League|2018]]\n}}\n{{Location map+ |Europe |width=380 |float=right |caption=Locations of the five stages and the Superfinal of the '''2017 Euro Beach Soccer League'''|places=\n{{Location map~ |Europe |lat=44.816667 |long=20.466667 |label=<small>''Stage 1'', '''[[Belgrade]]'''</small>|position=right|mark=Yellow_pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~ |Europe |lat=55.75 |long=37.616667 |label=<small>''Stage 3'', '''[[Moscow]]'''</small>|position=right|mark=Yellow_pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~ |Europe |lat=39.6 |long=-9.066667  |label=<small>''Stage 2'', '''[[Nazar\u00e9, Portugal|Nazar\u00e9]]'''</small>|position=right|mark=Yellow_pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~ |Europe |lat=46.92393 |long=18.09012  |label=<small>''Stage 4'', '''[[Si\u00f3fok]]'''</small>|position=left|mark=Yellow_pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~ |Europe |lat=54.166667 |long=12.083333  |label=<small>''Stage 5'', '''[[Warnem\u00fcnde]]'''</small>|position=right|mark=Yellow_pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~ |Europe |lat=41.2964 |long=13.2333 |label=<small>''Superfinal'', '''[[Terracina]]'''</small>|position=left|mark=Blue_pog.svg}}\n}}\nThe '''2017 [[Euro Beach Soccer League]] (EBSL)''' was the 20th edition of the annual, premier European competition in [[beach soccer]] contested between men's national teams, in a league and play-off format.\n\nThis season teams continued to take part in two divisions, the top tier (Division A) and the bottom tier (Division B). Twelve teams continued to contest Division A as in recent seasons, consisting of the top eleven finishers from last year plus [[Azerbaijan national beach soccer team|Azerbaijan]] who were promoted to the top tier. Division B was expanded to accommodate fifteen nations; the thirteen nations which did not gain promotion from last season, [[Lithuania national beach soccer team|Lithuania]] who made their debut, plus [[Romania national beach soccer team|Romania]] who were relegated from the top tier. No nations returned to the tournament after an absence from competing in recent years.\n\nThis season, in recognition of the 20th anniversary of the competition, additional matches were scheduled for a total of five ''stages'' of fixtures during the [[regular season]]. Each team from Division A played in two stages whilst each team from Division B played in one stage. During each stage the participating nations earned points for the overall league tables.\n\nAt the end of the regular season stages, according to the league tables, the eight best teams in Division A advanced to the [[post-season]] Superfinal to compete directly to become the winners of this year's EBSL. Meanwhile, the top seven teams in Division B (the stage winners and best runners-up) and the team ranked bottom of Division A played in the Promotion Final to try to earn a spot in Division A next year.\n\n[[Turkey national beach soccer team|Turkey]] were promoted to Division A after beating [[Estonia national beach soccer team|Estonia]] to claim the Promotion Final title. This sees Turkey return to the top flight for the first time since they were relegated from Division A in [[2011 Euro Beach Soccer League|2011]]. [[Greece national beach soccer team|Greece]] finished last in Division A and failed to defend their place in the Promotion Final and were therefore subsequently relegated to Division B, ending their four-year run in the top tier.\n\n[[Russia national beach soccer team|Russia]] won the league after a strong performance in the Superfinal, claiming their fifth EBSL crown to tie for first with [[Spain national beach soccer team|Spain]] and [[Portugal national beach soccer team|Portugal]] with the most titles in EBSL history. Defending champions [[Ukraine national beach soccer team|Ukraine]] were knocked out of title-winning contention in the group stage of the Superfinal, ultimately finishing seventh in the post-season event.\n\n== Calendar and locations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"200\"| Dates\n!width=\"120\"| Country\n!width=\"120\"| City\n!width=\"250\"| Stage\n|-\n| 23\u201325 June || {{flag|Serbia}} || [[Belgrade]] || Stage 1\n|-\n| 7\u20139 July || {{flag|Portugal}} || [[Nazar\u00e9, Portugal|Nazar\u00e9]] || Stage 2\n|-\n| 28\u201330 July || {{flag|Russia}} || [[Moscow]] || Stage 3\n|-\n| 11\u201313 August || {{flag|Hungary}} || [[Si\u00f3fok]] || Stage 4\n|-\n| 25\u201327 August || {{flag|Germany}} || [[Warnem\u00fcnde]] || Stage 5\n|-\n| 14\u201317 September|| {{flag|Italy}} || [[Terracina]] || Superfinal and Promotion Final\n|}\n\n==Teams==\n[[File:2017 EBSL map of nations.png|thumb|400px|{{legend|#67E863|Competing in '''Division A'''}} {{legend|#6085EF|Competing in '''Division B'''}} {{legend|#F36971|Competed in previous editions but not this year}} {{legend|#C3C3C3|Never competed in the EBSL}}]]\nThe following teams have entered this season, in the following divisions (12 in Division A, 15 in Division B).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theroonba.com/beachsoccer/men/fixtures.html|title=MEN'S BEACH SOCCER - FIXTURES|publisher=theroonba.com|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe numbers in brackets show the European ranking of each team prior to the start of the season, out of 36 nations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beachsoccer.com/ranking/overall |title=OVERALL WORLD RANKING |publisher=beachsoccer.com |date=8 June 2017 |accessdate=8 June 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608011017/http://beachsoccer.com/ranking/overall |archivedate=8 June 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Division A===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* {{beachsoccer|POR}} <small>(1st)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|RUS}} <small>(2nd)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|ITA}} <small>(3rd)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|SUI}} <small>(4th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|POL}} <small>(5th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|ESP}} <small>(6th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|UKR}} <small>(7th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|BLR}} <small>(9th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|FRA}} <small>(11th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|GER}} <small>(12th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|AZE}}<sup>'''[[#1|1]]'''</sup> <small>(14th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|GRE}} <small>(15th)</small>\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Division B===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* {{beachsoccer|HUN}} <small>(8th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|ENG}} <small>(10th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|CZE}} <small>(13th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|TUR}} <small>(16th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|ROM}}<sup>'''[[#2|2]]'''</sup> <small>(17th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|EST}} <small>(18th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|MDA}} <small>(19th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|NED}} <small>(20th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|NOR}} <small>(21st)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|SRB}} <small>(22nd)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|BUL}} <small>(24th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|KAZ}} <small>(25th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|DEN}} <small>(26th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|AND}} <small>(27th)</small>\n* {{beachsoccer|LTU}}<sup>'''[[#3|3]]'''</sup> <small>(28th)</small>\n{{div col end}}\n{{smalldiv|\n'''Notes:'''\n:<div id=\"1\">1. Promoted from Division B at the end of the [[2016 Euro Beach Soccer League|2016 season]]</div>\n:<div id=\"2\">2. Relegated from Division A at the end of the 2016 season</div>\n:<div id=\"3\">3.