{"title_page": "Jacque Vaughn", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox NBA biography\n| name = Jacque Vaughn\n| image = Jacque Vaughn cropped.jpg\n| caption = Vaughn in 2007\n| team = Brooklyn Nets\n| position = Interim head coach\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1975|2|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| nationality = American\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 1\n| weight_lb = 190\n| highschool = [[John Muir High School (Pasadena, California)|John Muir]] ([[Pasadena, California]])\n| college = [[Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball|Kansas]] (1993\u20131997)\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 27\n| draft_year = 1997\n| draft_team = [[Utah Jazz]]\n| career_start = 1997\n| career_end = 2009\n| career_position = [[Point guard]]\n| career_number = 11\n| coach_start = 2010\n| coach_end = \n| years1 = {{nbay|1997|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2000|end}}\n| team1 = [[Utah Jazz]]\n| years2 = {{nbay|2001|full=y}}\n| team2 = [[Atlanta Hawks]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|2002|full=y}}\n| team3 = [[Orlando Magic]]\n| years4 = {{nbay|2003|full=y}}\n| team4 = Atlanta Hawks\n| years5 = {{nbay|2004|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2005|end}}\n| team5 = [[New Jersey Nets]]\n| years6 = {{nbay|2006|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2008|end}}\n| team6 = [[San Antonio Spurs]]\n| cyears1 = {{nbay|2010|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2011|end}}\n| cteam1 = San Antonio Spurs (assistant) \n| cyears2 = {{nbay|2012|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2014|end}}\n| cteam2 = Orlando Magic \n| cyears3 = {{nbay|2016|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2019|end}}\n| cteam3 = [[Brooklyn Nets]] (assistant)\n| cyears4 = {{nbay|2019|end}}\u2013present\n| cteam4 = Brooklyn Nets (interim HC)\n| highlights =\n* [[List of NBA champions|NBA champion]] ([[2007 NBA Finals|2007]])\n* 2\u00d7 Consensus second-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] ([[1996 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1996]], [[1997 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1997]])\n* [[Big Eight Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|Big Eight Player of the Year]] (1996)\n* No. 11 jersey [[Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball#Retired jerseys|retired by Kansas Jayhawks]]\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American MVP]] ([[1993 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|1993]])\n* First-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1993)\n* Second-team ''Parade'' All-American (1992)\n| stats_league = NBA\n| stat1label = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value = 3,463 (4.5 ppg)\n| stat2label = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value = 1,028 (1.3 rpg)\n| stat3label = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value = 1,919 (2.5 apg)\n| bbr = vaughja01\n}}\n'''Jacque Vaughn''' (born February 11, 1975) is an American former professional [[basketball]] coach and former player. He serves as interim head coach of the [[Brooklyn Nets]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA).\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===High school===\nA native of Pasadena, California, Vaughn attended [[John Muir High School]] in nearby [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]], where he maintained a 3.94 GPA in honors and AP courses,{{citation needed|date=July 2012}} and became the best high school player in that area since former Muir and NBA standout [[Stacey Augmon]]. Vaughn excelled both on and off the court, and by his senior year was ranked as high as the no. 7 high school recruit in the country and the no. 2 point guard in the class of 1993 behind arguably the nation's top player that year, [[Randy Livingston]]. Over the course of the season, Vaughn averaged over 21 points and 19 assists per game, while also compiling six [[triple-doubles]]. Named a First-Team All-American by nearly every publication on the market, Vaughn rounded off his special season with a selection to participate in the prestigious [[McDonald's All-American Game]] where he put on a show, scoring only 6 points but amassing 13 assists (still a McDonald's record), while also thoroughly outplaying the higher-ranked Livingston once again\u2014this time on a national stage (they had both matched up against each other in the All-Star Game of the 1992 Nike Camp), and was named co-MVP with [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|North Carolina]]'s [[Jerry Stackhouse]] in the process. After considering [[Georgetown University|Georgetown]], [[Indiana University Bloomington|Indiana]], [[UNLV]], [[University of Arizona|Arizona]] and [[UCLA]], Vaughn decided to play for coach [[Roy Williams (coach)|Roy Williams]] at [[University of Kansas|Kansas]], continuing, along with fellow recruit and college roommate [[Scot Pollard]], the California pipeline of high school hoopsters to [[Lawrence, Kansas]], started by former standouts [[Adonis Jordan]] and [[Rex Walters]], and continuing in later years with [[Paul Pierce]], and [[Eric Chenowith]].\n\nAs a senior in high school in 1993, Vaughn was awarded the [[Dial Award]] as the nation's top male high school scholar-athlete, becoming the first basketball player ever to win that award.\n\n===College===\nIn his college career Vaughn became the starting point guard as a freshman after being chosen to replace incumbent starter Calvin Rayford. Among his first-year highlights were earning the MVP award at the 1993 Pre-Season NIT at [[Madison Square Garden]] in [[New York City]] and hitting a game-winning three pointer at the overtime buzzer to beat Indiana in an early season game at [[Allen Fieldhouse]].<ref>{{cite web |title=College Basketball Roundup: Vaughn's Shoy Lifts No. 6 Kansas Over Indiana |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1993-12-23-sp-4783-story.html |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |date=December 23, 1993}}</ref> Throughout his four years at Kansas, Vaughn was known as a good distributor of the basketball and effective defender with great speed and court awareness. By the end of his college career, he was the all-time leader in assists in Kansas basketball history with 804 total (since surpassed by [[Aaron Miles (basketball)|Aaron Miles]]), as well as the Big Eight Conference's all-time record holder. In 1997, the award given annually to the school's assist leader was renamed to include Vaughn, Miles and original assists leader, [[Cedric Hunter]], as the Hunter/Vaughn/Miles Assists Award.\n\nVaughn earned a 3.72 GPA as a Business Administration major.<ref>{{cite news|title=BHSN: Orlando Magic hire Jacque Vaughn as new head coach|url=http://www.cfnews13.com/content/news/cfnews13/sports/article.html/content/news/articles/cfn/2012/7/28/bhsn_orlando_magic_h.html|newspaper=Central Florida News|date=July 28, 2012}}</ref> He was a two-time Academic All-American at Kansas and the 1997 GTE Academic All-American of the Year. He was also a two-time all-conference pick and was named the [[Big Eight Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|Big Eight Player of the Year]] in 1996. His college jersey was retired on December 31, 2002 and hangs in the rafters of [[Allen Fieldhouse]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jacque Vaughn|work=KUSports.com|url=http://6news.kusports.com/intherafters/vaughn.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051221100929/http://6news.kusports.com/intherafters/vaughn.html|archivedate=December 21, 2005}}</ref>\n\n===Professional===\nIn 1997, Vaughn was selected 27th overall by the [[Utah Jazz]] in the [[1997 NBA draft]]. In addition to playing four seasons in Utah, Vaughn also played with the [[Orlando Magic]], the [[Atlanta Hawks]] (in two separate stints), [[New Jersey Nets]], and [[San Antonio Spurs]]. He appeared in 64 games for the NBA champion San Antonio Spurs during the 2006\u201307 season and finished his career there, retiring after the 2008\u201309 season. Over his career, he averaged 4.5 points per game and 2.5 assists per game. He also set an NBA record for consecutive missed field goal attempts to open a season, missing his first 22 to start the 2001 season with the [[Atlanta Hawks]]. After those 22 straight misses he shot a career best 47% that season.\n\n==NBA career playing statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend|champion=y}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1997}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1997\u201398 Utah Jazz season|Utah]]\n| 45 || 0 || 9.3 || .361 || .375 || .706 || .8 || 1.9 || .2 || .0 || 3.1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1998\u201399 Utah Jazz season|Utah]]\n| 19 || 0 || 4.6 || .367 || .250 || .833 || .6 || .6 || .3 || .0 || 2.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1999|trunc=y}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1999\u20132000 Utah Jazz season|Utah]]\n| 78 || 0 || 11.3 || .416 || .412 || .750 || .8 || 1.6 || .4 || .0 || 3.7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2000}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2000\u201301 Utah Jazz season|Utah]]\n| '''82''' || 0 || 19.8 || .433 || .385 || .780 || 1.8 || 3.9 || .6 || .0 || 6.1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2001}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2001\u201302 Atlanta Hawks season|Atlanta]]\n| '''82''' || 16 || '''22.6''' || '''.470''' || .444 || .825 || '''2.0''' || '''4.3''' || '''.8''' || .0 || '''6.6'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2002}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2002\u201303 Orlando Magic season|Orlando]]\n| 80 || '''48''' || 21.1 || .448 || .235 || .776 || 1.5 || 2.9 || '''.8''' || .0 || 5.9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2003}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2003\u201304 Atlanta Hawks season|Atlanta]]\n| 71 || 6 || 17.9 || .386 || .150 || .779 || 1.6 || 2.7 || .6 || .0 || 3.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2004}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2004\u201305 New Jersey Nets season|New Jersey]]\n| 71 || 34 || 19.9 || .449 || .333 || .835 || 1.5 || 1.9 || .6 || .0 || 5.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2005}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2005\u201306 New Jersey Nets season|New Jersey]]\n| 80 || 6 || 15.4 || .437 || .167 || .728 || 1.1 || 1.5 || .5 || .0 |